91. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638404134
T1  - Hypercapnia Impairs Endoplasmic Reticulum Function and Decreases Plasma Membrane Abundance of the Na,K-ATPase in Alveolar Epithelial Cells and Precision-Cut Lung Slices
T3  - International Conferenceof the American Thoracic Society, ATS 2022. San Francisco, CA United States.
A1  - Kryvenko V.
A1  - Wessendorf M.
A1  - Sznajder J.
A1  - Seeger W.
A1  - Vadasz I. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background: Maturation and folding of the Na,K-ATPase in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) are critically required for delivery of the transporter to the plasma membrane. Elevated CO2 levels have been previously found to negatively impact on Na,K-ATPase plasma membrane abundance, thus decreasing alveolar fluid clearance. The Na,K-ATPase beta-subunit plays a key role in delivery and insertion of the transporter into the plasma membrane. In the current study, we evaluated the role of hypercapnia on ER maturation of the Na,K-ATPase beta-subunit. Methods and Results: Hypercapnia (pCO2=120 mmHg; pHe=7.4) decreased Na,K-ATPase plasma membrane abundance in alveolar epithelial cells and murine precision cut lung slices, as assessed by cell surface biotinylation and confocal microscopy. Exposure to elevated CO2 levels established different short- and long-term mechanisms of Na,K-ATPase regulation. Short-term exposure to hypercapnia (up to 1 h), resulted in ER-associated degradation (ERAD) of the Na,K-ATPase beta-subunit via depletion of ER Ca2+ stores followed by phosphorylation and subsequent activation of serine/threonine-protein kinase/endoribonuclease inositol-requiring enzyme 1alpha (IRE1alpha). Moreover, ER alpha-mannosidase I (MAN1B1) and ER degradation enhancing alpha-mannosidase like protein 1 (EDEM1) were identified as key players involved in the degradation of the beta-subunit of the transporter. Genetic or chemical inhibition of ERAD machinery or IRE1alpha was sufficient to stabilize the levels of Na,KATPase at the plasma membrane. In contrast to short-term regulation, exposure of cells to elevated CO2 levels for up to 72 h resulted in ER retention of the Na,K-ATPase beta-subunit. Furthermore, hypercapnia induced mitochondrial dysfunction, increased protein oxidation in the ER and caused disruption of Na,K-ATPase alpha:beta-complex formation, thus preventing delivery of the transporter to the Golgi. Of note, altered ER homeostasis activated the unfolded proteins response. Treatment with alpha- ketoglutaric acid reduced the hypercapnia-induced oxidation in the ER and rescued the transporter abundance at the plasma membrane. Conclusion(s): Collectively, we provide evidence that elevated CO2 levels disturb maturation of the Na,K-ATPase beta-subunit in the ER thus preventing delivery of transporter to the plasma membrane. Understanding the mechanisms by which high CO2 levels impair ER maturation of proteins may provide novel therapeutic approaches in the treatment of acute and chronic lung diseases associated with hypercapnia.
