236. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001763968
T1  - Regression of polycystic ovary morphology on ultrasound and improvement of PCOS as per Rotterdam diagnostic criteria after multimodal naturopathic care
T3  - International Congress on Complementary Medicine Research: Pathways and Partnerships. Brisbane Australia.
A1  - Caut C.
A1  - Leach M.
A1  - Steel A. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a significant public health problem with reproductive, metabolic and psychological features. Conventional management ranges from lifestyle education, pharmacological treatment to IVF. Treatment approaches that improve PCOS are needed. Treatment practices of naturopaths and the outcomes of naturopathic care as it relates to the Rotterdam diagnostic criteria for PCOS should be further explored. Case summary: A female (28 years) diagnosed with PCOS with clinical evidence of hyperandrogenism (acne), ovulatory dysfunction (secondary amenorrhoea) and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound (right ovary: 54 antral follicles <10 mm; left ovary: 47 antral follicles <10 mm). Naturopathic treatment consisted of: dietary counselling to facilitate a low glycaemic load dietary intake; herbal medicines - Paeonia lactiflora, Glycyrrhiza glabra, Actaea racemosa, Thuja occidentalis, Tribulus terrestris, Gymnema sylvestre; and nutrients - chromium, zinc and vitamin c. Outcome(s): Within the first month of treatment, a menstrual bleed occurred. After 6 weeks of treatment acne improved, but not fully resolved. Inositol was prescribed followed by another menstrual bleed the following month. After 16 weeks of treatment, clinical symptoms of hyperandrogenism (ance) and ovulatory dysfunction improved and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound showed a reduction in the number of antral follicles < 10 mm in both ovaries (right ovary 39 antral follicles and left ovary 29 antral follicles < 10 mm) followed by another menstrual bleed. Implications: Naturopathic treatment of PCOS may have clinical implications which can be measured objectively through Rotterdam diagnostic criteria for PCOS. Further research is needed to explore the overall clinical effect of multimodal naturopathic care.Copyright © 2019
