A1  - Mc Keating A.
A1  - Turner M.J.
A1  - Daly S. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Predictors of Gestational Diabetes Mellitus(GDM) include age, body mass index (BMI), family history of diabetes mellitus(DM) and a history of PCOS. Among the strongest predictors of GDM is BMI. However, BMI is a crude marker for adiposity. Body composition assesses fat mass, fat free mass and visceral fat. These may be a more accurate predictor of GDM. Body composition using bioelectrical impedance analysis(BIA) is safe and reproducible in pregnancy. BIA uses segmental limb volume which allows for variance in pregnancy with the gravid uterus. This differs from other methods which take the maternofetal and placental unit as being a single entity. The aim of this study is examine which elements of body composition measurements taken before 16 weeks gestation are the strongest predictors of GDM in an at risk group of women. STUDY DESIGN: This was a prospective,longitudinal,observational secondary analysis of 208 women with singleton pregnancies who were included in an larger RCTassessing the effects of inositol on the development of GDM. Women were recruited at 10-16 weeks. Maternal height was measured using a wall mounted stadiometer. Maternal body composition was measured using segmental multifrequency bioelectrical impedance analysis. All women were at risk of GDM due to a family history of DM and were, therefore, booked for a one-step 75g oral glucose tolerance test(OGTT) between 24-28 weeks. RESULT(S): There were 208 women in the study, of which n=42 (20.2%) developed GDM. The mean age was 31.4 +/-5.1 and the mean BMI was 25.9 +/-4.5. Of the 208 women, n=68 (32.7%) were primips, n=154 (74.0%) were Caucasian, n=14 (6.7%) were smokers, n=65 (31.3%) were overweight and n=33 (15.9%) were obese (BMI >= 29.9kg/m2). The mean fat mass was 23.6kg +/- 10.4kg, the mean free fat mass was 47.5kg +/-6.8kg and the mean visceral fat was 4.5 +/-2.8. These were compared using linear regression to estimate the strongest predictor of GDM. For free fat mass the value of R2 was 0.27 (p=0.17), for fat mass the value of R2 was 0.42 (p=0.03) and the value of R2 was 0.60 (p<0.001) (Table 1). CONCLUSION(S): Visceral fat measured using BIA before 16 weeks gestation was the strongest predictor for the development of GDM. Fat mass the next strongest predictor for GDM, while free fat mass was a weak predictor.
