463. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70906140
T1  - Myo-inositol vs D-Chiro inositol in pcos treatment
T3  - 20th FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rome Italy.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Ciotta L.
A1  - Formuso C.
A1  - Pagano I.
A1  - Stracquadanio M. 
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Objectives: The aim of our study is to compare the clinical, endocrine and metabolic response after 6 months of therapy in 111 PCOS women, treated with Myo-inositol or with D-Chiro-Inositol or with Placebo. Materials: During the 6 months of enrollment, 111 women affected by PCOS (mean age: 25+/-2.4 years. BMI: 28+/-1.3 kg/m2) were selected. The patients were characterized by Oligomenorrhea and/or Acne (2.5+/-0.5, evaluated by Cremoncini score) and/or mild Hirsutism (<15, evaluated by Ferriman-Gallwey score) and Insulin-Resistance (3.2+/-0.6 evaluated by HOMA-IR). According to a randomized double blind, the patients were divided into 3 groups: - Group A (40 Patients), treated with 2 g of myo-inositol (+ folic acid) twice a day, per os - Group B (42 Patients), treated with D-chiro-Inositol (+ folic acid, B12 vitamin and Manganese) 500mg twice a day, per os - Group C (29 patients) treated with multivitaminic placebo without folic acid, B12 vitamin and Manganese, twice a day, per os. Method(s): Before treatment, and after 6 months of therapy, were evaluated Clinical Subjective and Objective Parameters (Menstrual- Cycle, Acne Score and Hirsutism Score), Metabolic Parameters (Total cholesterol, HDL-cholesterol, LDL-cholesterol, Triglycerides, Glycemia, Insulinemia and HOMA-IR) and Endocrine Parameters (LH, FSH, PRL, Total T, fT, D4-A, 17-OH-P, DHEA, DHEA-S, SHBG). Result(s): After 6 months of therapy, our study showed a significant improvement of the regularity of the menstrual-cycle in the 64% of the Group A (P < 0.001) and in the 62% of the Group B (P < 0.001). A significant improvement of Acne Score was detected in Groups A and B (respectively, 59% of the Group A and 63% of the Group B, P < 0.05 in both Groups). No relevant improvement was detected in all patients concerning Hirsutism Score. A significant decrease of DHEA (P < 0.05), DHEA-S (P < 0.05) and fT (P < 0.05) and an increase of SHBG (P < 0.05) serum levels were noticed in Groups A and B. A significant decrease of Triglycerides (P < 0.05), Total Cholesterol (P < 0.05), Basal Insulin serum levels (P < 0.05) and HOMA-IR (P < 0.05) was found in Groups A and B. (Figure Presented) Conclusion(s): Our study showed that both Myo-Inositol and D-Chiro Inositol treatments are able to improve the regularity of the menstrual-cycle, Acne Score, endocrine and metabolic parameters, and IR, in young overweight PCOS patients. We assumed that both treatments with Myo-inositol and with D-Chiro inositol could be proposed as a potential valid therapeutic approach for PCOS patients.
