A1  - Pellicer A.
A1  - Garrido N. 
Y1  - 2011//
N2  - Introduction: Basic sperm analysis present obvious limitations to predict male infertility and pregnancy achievement in assisted reproduction techniques (ARTs), as well as to explain the molecular causes (i.e.: MRNA expression profile or DNA oxidation) involving ART failure, especially in homologous intrauterine insemination (IUI-H) procedures. New tools are being developed to improve sperm analysis' predictive capacity. To this end, massive testing equipments such as microarray platforms are interesting options to be employed. Our group previously showed profound mRNA expression differences in pooled sperm samples achieving or not pregnancy by IUI-H. With this initial approach, individual variability was not considered, having the possibility to present outliers of the main population thus yielding biased results, but enabled to list the most relevant candidate genes related with pregnancy achievement. In order to develop a more specific microarray based predictive tool, there is a need to evaluate this from individualized sample's mRNA analysis. Our aim with this work is to use microarray technology to characterize differential gene expression profiles in individualized sperm samples (SS) from infertile patients (IP) achieving or not pregnancy in IUI-H cycles in order to determine genes linked to pregnancy establishment. Material(s) and Method(s): We designed a nested cases and controls study with 16 SS obtained from normozoospermic IP, according to WHO 2010 guidelines, undergoing their first IUI-H cycle. All females were under 36 years old and did not present any evident infertility problems associated, such as polycystic ovarian syndrome or tubaric obstruction or endometriosis. Sperm mRNA was extracted using Trizol protocol, suspended in DEPC-treated water and frozen at -80degreeC until the microarray experiments were performed. After mRNA extraction of the SS employed for IUI-H cycle from individual patients accomplishing the inclusion criteria, we identified samples from which pregnancy was achieved (P, n = 7) or not (NP, n = 9). The results were evaluated to detect those genes differentially expressed (GDE). Three criteria were used to define GDE in the different sample sets: Genes that were common in both groups, showing an absolute fold change expression (FCE) of = >2.0 times and a corresponding fold change p-value < 0.05). Finally, 16 microarray experiments were performed, one per SS. Result(s): After the bioinformatic analysis we found 15 GDE presenting increased expression in all 7 SS from group P, being the three most differentially expressed: Homo sapiens solute carrier family 5 (inositol transporters), member 3 (SLC5A3) with FCE of 4.7, Homo sapiens chromosome 12 open reading frame 28 (C12orf28) with FCE of 4.4 and Homo sapiens prolactin-induced protein (PIP) with a FCE of 2.6, whereas 52 GDE presented increased expression in all 9 SS forming NP group, being the three most differentially expressed the Homo sapiens G protein-coupled receptor 109B (GPR109B)with FCE of 10.9, Homo sapiens inhibin, beta A (activin A, activin AB alpha polypeptide) (INHBA) with a FCE of 6.1 and Homo sapiens indoleamine-pyrrole 2,3 dioxygenase (INDO) with a FCE of 5.6. Conclusion(s): Previous works of our group reported differences when SS pools from IP undergoing IUI-H achieving or not pregnancy were compared, now this work also reveals profound differences between expression profiles when individually SS which achieved pregnancy vs. those unable in IUH-I cycle were compared. This new information is useful in order to design a customized microarray for sperm to reveal molecular basis of sperm pathophysiology in depth, thus complementing and improving the diagnostic accuracy of the basic sperm analysis.
