476. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70389764
T1  - FSH alone?
T3  - 9th Annual Meeting of the Mediterranean Society for Reproductive Medicine: Modern ART in the 21st Century. Paris France.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Fusi F.M. 
Y1  - 2011//
N2  - Introduction: The induction of ovulation in PCO and PCO's patients has always been a challenge for the clinician. In many cases the mono-follicular ovulation seems not to be possible. When the therapeutic decision is IVF, PCO patients risk the yield of a great number of poor quality oocytes, and to undergo OHSS. Several attempts have been done to tailor the induction of ovulation for these patients. Method(s): Our approach to the induction of ovulation for PCO patients varied greatly from the simple approach: long protocol-FSH alone, that was mostly used in the past. First of all, we introduced myo-inositol for some months in the preparation of these patients. This has an effect in lowering insulin-resistance and improving the androgen transformation to estrogens. Second, we shifted to a protocol with antagonist, giving the possibility of triggering ovulation using the agonist. Third, in some cases the addition of LH activity when the leads follicles are 14mm leads to the selection of higher quality follicles and the atresia of the smallest ones, via the increase of intra-follicular androgens Results: In this paper are presented the results of our experience. The use of myoinositol gives a lower number of oocytes but of greater quality. The use of a short protocol with antagonists allowed us to obtain a dramatic drop in the OHSS, with oocytes of good quality. The shift from a stimulation with only FSH to an LH activity in the last days allowed us to reduce the risk of OHSS and to obtain anyway better oocytes. Conclusion(s): Our results show that for PCO patients, even when it is not necessary to use other medications, such as metformin, the personalization of the therapy gives better results. The era of the FSH alone for PCO is over.
