498. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70467155
T1  - Investigation of the effect of diabetes-associated factors on renal inositol regulation
T3  - 46th Annual Scientific Meeting of the Australian and New Zealand Society of Nephrology. Perth, WA Australia.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Chang H.
A1  - Walker C.
A1  - Choong B.
A1  - Loomes K. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - Inositol and its phosphate derivatives are involved in membrane structuring, various signal transductions and osmoregulation and are believed to be important in normal cellular functions. Disturbance in inositol homeostasis has been associated with numerous diseases. These include diabetes mellitus, polycystic ovary syndrome and several psychological disorders. Excess urinary inositol excretion and tissue inositol depletion have been observed in diabetic subjects and animal models. Furthermore, these inositol abnormalities have been implicated on the development of chronic diabetic complications. However, the underlying mechanisms are not well understood. myo-inositol oxygenase (MIOX) is the first committing enzyme in the only inositol catabolic pathway and is speculated to be crucial in inositol regulation. Since MIOX is predominately expressed in kidney, the aim of this study is to investigate how the expressions of MIOX and other inositol regulatory genes are influenced by diabetes-associated factors in the kidney. These factors include hyperglycemia, insulin resistance and hypertension. MIOX expressions, at both mRNA and protein level, are significantly elevated by all three factors examined when comparing with the corresponding controls. Furthermore, MIOX activity was also elevated by all three factors when comparing with controls. These findings suggest an enhanced inositol catabolism capability by diabetes-associated factors.
