508. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70197181
T1  - Addition of myo-inositol to clomiphene citrate in PCOS patients clomiphene-resistant for ovulation induction
T3  - 25th Annual Meeting of the European Society of Human Reproduction and Embryology, ESHRE. Amsterdam Netherlands.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Papaleo E.
A1  - De Santis L.
A1  - Baillergeon J.P.
A1  - Serafini A.
A1  - Potenza M.T.
A1  - Fusi F.M.
A1  - Brigante C. 
Y1  - 2009//
N2  - Introduction: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is often characterized by chronic oligoovulation or anovulation and hyperandrogenism. PCO's patients are sub-fertile and often need drugs for ovulation induction, as clomifene citrate (CC), which increase risk of multiple pregnancy and hyperstimulation syndrome. Furthermore 20-25% of patients do not ovulate with 50 mg protocol, and need to increase dose to 100-150 mg, with comparable increasing of complications. Thirty to 40 percent of PCOS women have impaired glucose tolerance, and a defect in the insulin signal pathway (inositol-containing phosphoglycan mediators) seems to be implicated in the pathogenesis of insulin resistance. For this reason insulin-lowering medications represent novel therapies for restoring a spontaneous ovulation; in fact the administration of different isoforms of inositol as D-Chiro-inositol (DCI) or myo-inositol (MYO) is demonstrated improving the physiological insulin-receptor activity, restoring spontaneous ovulatory function in most of PCO's women. Aim of the study was to evaluate the effectiveness of a pre-treatment and co-treatment with MYO to the standard therapy of CC in 50 mg CC resistant patients. Materials&methods: Our observational study included 12 PCOS anovulatory patients who failed to ovulate with 50 mg CC standard protocol. We pre-treated those women with daily 4 g myo-inositol plus 400 mg folic acid (Inofolicw, LO.LI Pharma) orally for a period of minimum 30 days. At the subsequent menstrual bleeding all patients, continuing MYO at the same dose, started CC (Clomidw, Bruno Farmaceutici) ovulation induction protocol maintaining 50 mg per day, for five days. 5000 UI of hCG were administered if no more than 2 follicles .18 mm were found at ultrasound monitoring. Primary end-point was overall ovulation rate. Secondary end-point was mono-ovulation rates and pregnancy rates. Result(s): Four patients were MYO plus 50 mg CC resistant while eight out of twelve restored ovulation with the minimal dose of CC (ovulation rate was 66.6%). Five out of eight patients showed a mono-ovulation, while two presented a total of 2 follicles. One patient was suspended as result of the growth of four follicles .16-18 mm diameter. A total of three pregnancies were achieved. One of them was a twin pregnancy, in a patients who developed two follicles, while two singletons were obtained in mono-ovulating patients. No side effects were reported with MYO. Conclusion(s): Myo-inositol, acting as an insulin sensitizer compound and/or as a post-receptor messenger, seems to be capable to restore spontaneous sensitivity of ovaries to hormonal stimulation. These effects are useful in PCOS women with ovulatory disorders, since the standard hormonal treatment in a considerable part of such patients is ineffective both for failed or exaggerate response. In the treatment of PCOS, the combination of MYO plus 50 mg CC could represent the standard approach, not only for CC resistant patients, but rather for all of them, with the purpose to reduce both failed response and multiple follicle growth, and consequently the risk of multiple pregnancy.
