509. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70197010
T1  - Preventive BMI reduction increase ovarian response and pregnancy rate in Myo-inositol and r-FSH in stimulated cycles of anovulatory obese women
T3  - 25th Annual Meeting of the European Society of Human Reproduction and Embryology, ESHRE. Amsterdam Netherlands.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Infante Vincenzo V.I.
A1  - D'Aniello Gemma D.G.
A1  - Irollo A.M.I.A.
A1  - Ronsini Salvatore R.S. 
Y1  - 2009//
N2  - Introduction: Metformin is the most extensively studied insulin-sensitizing agent for the treatment of women with PCOS and obesity. Other insulin-sensitizing agents studied include troglitazone, rosiglitazone, pioglitazone, and inositol. Since the administration of an isoform of inositol (myo-inositol), belonging to the vitamin B complex, has been used to restore a normal ovulatory function improving the insulin-receptor activity, as well as to improve oocytes quality in ICSI cycles. The aim of our study was to assess if the association of inositol assumption with a preventive reduction of Body Mass Index (BMI) improves the controlled ovarian stimulation (COS) parameters in programmed sexual intercourses of anovulatory obese women (who have already two failed spontaneous monitored ovulation cycles.) Material(s) and Method(s): Ovulatory activity of fifty anovulatory obese women (BMI >= 30) (no tubal or deficiency of male semen parameters was found) in programmed sexual intercourses stimulated whit recombinant FSH (a-rFSH, Merck-Serono) was monitored with ultrasound scan and hormonal profile. Endpoint registered were the numbers of follicles obtained and of cancelled cycles, E2 peak at hCG administration and pregnancy rate. The patients were divided in two randomized groups as followed: 25 obese subjects (Group A) received myo-inositol combined with folic acid (Inofolic. LO.LI. Pharma) 2 g twice a day plus 150 UI of rFSH/die until at least a follicle.18 mm, and 25 (Group B) obese women received the same inositol and rFSH dosage only when their BMI was<=28 after a diet program of 1350 kcal/die. Result(s): All women were comparable in terms of age, cause and duration of infertility. In both groups there weren't stimulation cycles cancelled. In the group A, the mean number of follicles .18 mm obtained was 1+/-0,2 versus 2+/-0,4 of the group B.(100%) Peak E2 levels at hCG administration were (significantly) lower in patients receiving only myo-inositol and r-FSH in respect to patients that preventively have reduced their BMI through controlled diet in the previous weeks (135,28+/2 46,89 vs 341,17+/2 61,61 pg/mL), (60%) Only one out of 25 (4%) patients among group A become pregnant, resulting in an evolutive pregnancy. In contrast, group B exhibited 7 (28%) evolutive pregnancy and these differences were statistically significant (P = 0,04). Conclusion(s): Treatment with myo-inositol is largely diffused in the management of anovulatory disease being involved in insuline metabolism. Our data showed that the use of myo-inositol associated with rFSH in obese anovulatory woman allows to obtain at least one dominant follicle in all patients studied. Furthermore, this effect seems to be more efficace if it was preceded by a diet regimen in the previous weeks, in fact we've observed an improved ovarian response to stimulation, greater levels of E2 peak and significant higher pregnancy rate. Probably the reduction of BMI and the consequent loss of Fat Mass was more effective than the only use of inositol in anovulatory obese patients. Further studies will confirm if this approach may be used routinely in stimulated cycles of mild overweight infertile woman too.
