520. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 354336716
T1  - Historical background and review of drugs and methods used for induction of ovulation part II
A1  - Rajab K.E.
A1  - Sequeira R.P.
A1  - Essa A.A. 
Y1  - 2008//
N2  - Over the last four decades great advancement has been achieved in the field of the newly invented drugs for use in ovulation induction. Parallel to these discoveries a vast understanding has been reached in the micro physiology of the ovarian functions and the hormonal interactions along the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian-axis. The introduction of IVF in clinical practice also played a pivotal rule in this change and has since increased the use of OI in practice. Contributions from other medical sciences such as genetics, endocrinology, immunology, biochemistry and cytogenetics to the art of ART have all played a role in making induction of ovulation a science in its own right. Despite the plethora of effective fertility drugs, there are now new and innovative medications which proved to be promising, but still await clinical evaluation. In our current OI practice, however. there are two overriding issues in selecting treatment protocols. firstly, the costs of the treatment and secondly, safety of patients. Fertility drugs and the high technology monitoring required by the patients are expensive. It is estimated that in the USA the cost of each cycle varies between $5000 to 20000. This is a heavy burden on patients in the US and nearly out of reach option for patients in developing countries. In Europe, health policies dictated that patients must share the cost of fertility drugs, but this policy has not been tried in our health services. This can explain also why most of fertilitv treatment clinics are in the private sector. The safety of fertility drugs is also under scrutiny. Apart from the OHSS which can be serious in certain instances requiring 'Intensive Care', other condition like DVT/PE and the long term risk of ovarian cancer have been reported. The results of several studies on the cancer risk are still inconclusive. What can be done to minimize these complications are better drugs, safer protocol aiming at singleton pregnancy and the creation of specialized fertility units. There are other problems related to the current OI therapy such as ovarian hypersensitivity which are unpredictable. The other major problem is the difficulty in predicting poor ovarian response to drugs prior to starting therapy. So far this has been minimized through the utilization of several strategies like tailoring the treatment according to the serum estradiol which is monitored during the stimulation cycles; doing ultrasound measurements of the growing follicles; using, GnRH analogues to suppress LH effect or modifying the treatment protocol (e.g. use of long protocol) to avoid hyperstimulation. In poor response of ovaries to fertility drugs it is unavoidable to consider higher doses of gonadotropins if there is no initial ovarian responsiveness. Nevertheless, the result have been controversial as reported in prospective randomized trial which showed either minimal or no benefit. Additionally, the few available studies have suggested that the use of recombinant FSH might improve the outcome. Newer reports are suggesting beneficial results with. the use of flare-up GnRH agonist protocols along with high doses of gonadotropins. Pre treatment with combined OC may help the ovarian response and, appears to be beneficial. Likewise, the adjuvant therapy with GH or GH-releasing-factors in general is ineffective. The use of corticosteroids appears to reduce the incidence of poor response in the population undergoing IVF treatment. In conclusion, ovulation induction is a rapidly evolving clinical science with considerable potentials. The need for defining different treatment strategies is essential to assess their efficacy. There is a need also to reduce the cost and make it more accessible for those who need it. Health planners in Bahrain should include air ART service in the teaching hospital in order to cover needy patients, provide for teaching trainee staff, and material for medical rescarch.
