T1  - Effects of inositol hexaphosphate on the Bohr effect induced by CO2 and fixed acids in chicken hemoglobin
A1  - Weingarten J.P.
A1  - Rollema H.S.
A1  - Bauer C.
A1  - Scheid P. 
Y1  - 1978//
N2  - Bohr factors, phi = DELTA log PO2/D pH, were measured in chicken hemoglobin (Hb) solutions at various levels of O2 saturation in the absence and the presence of inositol hexaphosphate (IHP). pH changes were induced either by changing PCO2 at constant base excess near zero (CO2 Bohr factor, phiCO2) or by addition of fixed acid or base at constant PCO2 (fixed acid Bohr factor, phiAH). In the presence of IHP in a concentration of about 1.2 mol per mol Hb tetramer the two Bohr factors did not differ, the mean value being -0.71 (pH range, 7.1 to 7.6), independent of O2 saturation (SO2) between 10 and 90%. Removal of IHP significantly decreased phiAH to -0.25 (pH range, 7.0 to 7.6), independent of SO2, whereas the reduction in phiCO2 was much less pronounced. Thus phiCO2, which showed a decrease with increasing SO2, exceeded phiAH at all levels of SO2. The data show that chicken hemoglobin is capable of binding CO2 as oxygen-linked carbamate. But, at about equimolar concentrations of IHP and the tetrameric hemoglobin, oxylabile carbamate formation is abolished. It is suggested that this interaction between CO2 and the organic phosphate compound accounts for the lack of a difference between the two Bohr factors in avian whole blood (cf. Meyer et al., 1978) where inositol pentaphosphate is present at about the same concentration as tetrameric hemoglobin.
